** 1.1.3 What is the nature of causation?

*** 1.1.3.1 Catholic Response
Causation operates through four Aristotelian causes (material, formal, efficient, final) with God as primary cause working through secondary causes, requiring recognition of both natural causation and divine providence according to Thomistic causal analysis.

*** 1.1.3.2 Protestant Response
Causation derives entirely from God's sovereign decree and providence, with all secondary causes dependent upon divine primary causation, requiring recognition of divine sovereignty over all natural and historical processes according to Reformed theological understanding.

*** 1.1.3.3 Orthodox Response
Causation flows from divine energies working through natural processes blessed by Incarnation, with divine and natural causation cooperating in cosmic transfiguration according to Orthodox understanding of divine-human synergy.

*** 1.1.3.4 Jewish Response
Causation operates through divine providence (hashgaha) working through natural order established by divine wisdom, requiring human cooperation in divine plan through ethical action according to Jewish theological understanding.

*** 1.1.3.5 Islamic Response
Causation derives from Allah's continuous creation (khalq jadid) with all apparent causes dependent upon divine will, requiring recognition of Allah as ultimate cause behind all natural and historical processes according to Islamic occasionalist tendency.

*** 1.1.3.6 Hindu Response
Causation operates through karma and dharmic order with divine intervention (kripa) transcending mechanical necessity, requiring righteous action and spiritual practice according to Hindu theological understanding of cosmic justice.

*** 1.1.3.7 Buddhist Response
Causation flows through dependent origination (pratityasamutpada) without permanent agent or substance, requiring understanding of conditional arising and emptiness according to Buddhist causal analysis.

*** 1.1.3.8 Confucian Response
Causation manifests through moral principle and human cultivation with cosmic harmony requiring virtuous action, requiring ethical responsibility according to Confucian understanding of moral causation.

*** 1.1.3.9 Aristotelian Response
Causation operates through four causes (material, formal, efficient, final) with teleological orientation toward good, requiring philosophical investigation of natural purposes according to Aristotelian causal framework.

*** 1.1.3.10 Indigenous Response
Causation flows through spiritual relationships and sacred reciprocity with all beings participating in cosmic balance, requiring ceremonial maintenance of harmony according to indigenous understanding of relational causation.

*** 1.1.3.11 Roman Catholic Response
Causation operates through four Aristotelian causes under divine primary causation, requiring understanding of natural secondary causes serving divine providence according to Thomistic systematic analysis of causal hierarchy and divine governance.

*** 1.1.3.12 Eastern Catholic Response
Causation flows through divine energies working in natural processes, integrating Eastern understanding of divine-natural cooperation with Catholic sacramental causation according to Eastern Catholic theological synthesis.

*** 1.1.3.13 Traditional Catholic Response
Causation operates through immutable natural law and divine providence preserved in traditional teaching, requiring adherence to perennial causal analysis according to traditional Catholic philosophical framework.

*** 1.1.3.14 Catholic Religious Orders Response
Causation manifests through contemplative realization and apostolic action, requiring understanding of divine causation working through religious charisms according to monastic and mendicant traditions.

*** 1.1.3.15 Contemporary Catholic Response
Causation integrates through personalist philosophy and scientific dialogue, requiring contemporary understanding while maintaining traditional causal principles according to contemporary Catholic intellectual movements.

*** 1.1.3.16 Lutheran Response
Causation derives from divine sovereignty and forensic justification, requiring recognition of divine causation in salvation while maintaining natural causal order according to Lutheran theological understanding.

*** 1.1.3.17 Reformed/Presbyterian Response
Causation flows entirely from divine decree and absolute sovereignty, requiring recognition of divine primary causation determining all secondary causes according to Reformed systematic theology.

*** 1.1.3.18 Anglican/Episcopal Response
Causation operates through via media balancing divine and natural causation, requiring comprehensive understanding integrating Catholic and Protestant insights according to Anglican theological methodology.

*** 1.1.3.19 Baptist Response
Causation derives from divine sovereignty and individual responsibility, requiring recognition of divine providence while maintaining human accountability according to Baptist theological distinctives.

*** 1.1.3.20 Methodist/Wesleyan Response
Causation operates through prevenient grace and human cooperation, requiring understanding of divine-human synergy in salvation and sanctification according to Wesleyan theological framework.

*** 1.1.3.21 Eastern Orthodox Response
Causation flows through divine energies working in creation while preserving divine essence mystery, requiring understanding of energetic causation and cosmic transfiguration according to Orthodox patristic theology.

*** 1.1.3.22 Autocephalous Orthodox Response
