** 1.1.5 What is the nature of consciousness?

*** 1.1.5.1 Catholic Response
Consciousness consists in rational soul's immaterial operations of intellect and will participating in divine rational order, with human consciousness capable of knowing universal truth and choosing ultimate good according to Thomistic philosophical anthropology.

*** 1.1.5.2 Protestant Response
Consciousness reflects divine image corrupted by sin but restored through redemption, with true consciousness requiring spiritual regeneration and conformity to divine will according to Scripture and Reformed theological anthropology.

*** 1.1.5.3 Orthodox Response
Consciousness participates in divine image (imago Dei) and is destined for theosis through purification and illumination, with authentic consciousness requiring spiritual transformation and mystical participation according to Orthodox ascetical tradition.

*** 1.1.5.4 Jewish Response
Consciousness reflects divine image (tzelem Elohim) with capacity for moral choice and spiritual development, requiring ethical education and spiritual practice according to Jewish psychological and ethical understanding.

*** 1.1.5.5 Islamic Response
Consciousness (wa'y) reflects divine breath (ruh) with human fitrah naturally oriented toward divine recognition, requiring spiritual purification and submission to achieve authentic consciousness according to Islamic spiritual psychology.

*** 1.1.5.6 Hindu Response
Consciousness constitutes fundamental reality (chit) manifesting through individual awareness and cosmic consciousness, requiring yoga practice and self-inquiry to realize pure consciousness according to Vedantic psychological understanding.

*** 1.1.5.7 Buddhist Response
Consciousness arises through dependent origination lacking permanent self or substance, requiring mindfulness and meditation to understand consciousness-only reality according to Buddhist psychological analysis.

*** 1.1.5.8 Confucian Response
Consciousness embodies moral sensitivity and cultural refinement requiring education and social harmony, requiring virtue cultivation to develop authentic human consciousness according to Confucian psychological framework.

*** 1.1.5.9 Platonic Response
Consciousness participates in divine reason with rational soul capable of knowing eternal forms, requiring philosophical education to realize authentic intellectual consciousness according to Platonic psychological theory.

*** 1.1.5.10 Indigenous Response
Consciousness encompasses spiritual awareness and connection with all beings through sacred relationships, requiring ceremonial practice to maintain conscious harmony with natural and spiritual worlds according to indigenous psychology.

*** 1.1.5.11 Roman Catholic Response
Consciousness consists in rational soul's immaterial operations of intellect and will participating in divine rational order, requiring sacramental mediation and theological education to achieve supernatural consciousness according to Thomistic anthropological framework.

*** 1.1.5.12 Eastern Catholic Response
Consciousness participates in divine energies through liturgical blessing and contemplative practice, integrating Eastern understanding of spiritual consciousness with Catholic sacramental theology.

*** 1.1.5.13 Traditional Catholic Response
Consciousness maintains eternal rational structure through immutable natural law, requiring adherence to traditional moral formation and resistance to psychological modernism according to traditional Catholic anthropology.

*** 1.1.5.14 Catholic Religious Orders Response
Consciousness develops through contemplative realization and monastic discipline, requiring religious formation and spiritual direction according to specific contemplative charisms.

*** 1.1.5.15 Contemporary Catholic Response
Consciousness integrates through personalist philosophy and psychological dialogue, requiring engagement with contemporary consciousness studies while maintaining traditional anthropological principles.

*** 1.1.5.16 Lutheran Response
Consciousness reflects divine image affected by sin but restored through justification, requiring recognition of simul justus et peccator affecting entire conscious experience according to Lutheran anthropology.

