** 1.2.2 What are the limits of human knowledge?

*** 1.2.2.1 Catholic Response
Human knowledge reaches natural limits requiring supernatural revelation and divine grace for complete truth, with reason capable of demonstrating God's existence but needing faith for salvific knowledge according to Thomistic epistemological framework.

*** 1.2.2.2 Protestant Response
Human knowledge remains corrupted by sin requiring Scripture and Holy Spirit illumination for authentic understanding, with natural reason subordinated to revealed truth according to Reformed epistemological understanding.

*** 1.2.2.3 Jewish Response
Human knowledge finds completion through Torah study and rabbinic interpretation, with rational investigation serving divine revelation and ethical obligation according to Jewish intellectual tradition.

*** 1.2.2.4 Islamic Response
Human knowledge reaches limits requiring divine guidance through Quran and prophetic example, with rational investigation ('aql) serving revealed knowledge according to Islamic epistemological hierarchy.

*** 1.2.2.5 Hindu Response
Human knowledge transcends rational limitations through spiritual realization and guru guidance, with ordinary knowledge (paroksha) requiring direct experience (aparoksha) according to Vedantic epistemological distinction.

*** 1.2.2.6 Buddhist Response
Human knowledge remains limited by conceptual thinking and karmic conditioning, requiring meditative insight and wisdom cultivation to transcend intellectual limitations according to Buddhist epistemological understanding.

*** 1.2.2.7 Confucian Response
Human knowledge finds completion through moral cultivation and cultural wisdom, with intellectual investigation serving ethical development and social harmony according to Confucian educational framework.

*** 1.2.2.8 Platonic Response
Human knowledge reaches limits in sensible world requiring philosophical ascent to intelligible realm, with rational soul capable of eternal knowledge through dialectical education according to Platonic epistemological hierarchy.

*** 1.2.2.9 Kantian Response
Human knowledge remains limited to phenomena while noumena remain unknowable, requiring critical philosophy to understand transcendental conditions and practical reason according to Kantian epistemological critique.

*** 1.2.2.10 Indigenous Response
Human knowledge finds completion through spiritual relationship and ceremonial wisdom, with rational thinking requiring integration with sacred knowledge according to indigenous epistemological understanding.

*** 1.2.2.11 Roman Catholic Response
Human knowledge reaches natural limits requiring supernatural revelation and divine grace, with reason capable of demonstrating divine existence but needing faith for complete truth according to Thomistic epistemological framework and magisterial authority.

*** 1.2.2.12 Eastern Catholic Response
Human knowledge transcends rational limitations through divine energies and liturgical participation, integrating Eastern understanding of epistemological transcendence with Catholic sacramental theology.

*** 1.2.2.13 Traditional Catholic Response
Human knowledge maintains eternal rational structure through immutable principles, requiring adherence to traditional epistemological limits and resistance to modernist rationalism according to traditional Catholic framework.

*** 1.2.2.14 Catholic Religious Orders Response
Human knowledge finds completion through contemplative realization and monastic discipline, requiring religious formation transcending ordinary epistemological limitations according to contemplative traditions.

*** 1.2.2.15 Contemporary Catholic Response
Human knowledge integrates natural reason with supernatural revelation, requiring dialogue between contemporary methodology and traditional Catholic epistemological principles according to modern movements.

*** 1.2.2.16 Lutheran Response
Human knowledge remains corrupted by sin requiring Scripture and Holy Spirit illumination, with natural reason subordinated to revealed truth according to Lutheran epistemological understanding of fallen rationality.

*** 1.2.2.17 Reformed/Presbyterian Response
Human knowledge suffers total depravity requiring divine regeneration and systematic theological framework, with authentic understanding impossible without divine election according to Reformed epistemological limitation.

*** 1.2.2.18 Anglican/Episcopal Response
Human knowledge operates through via media balancing rational and revealed limitations, requiring comprehensive understanding integrating Catholic and Protestant epistemological insights according to Anglican methodology.

*** 1.2.2.19 Baptist Response
Human knowledge requires individual spiritual illumination and personal faith relationship, emphasizing scriptural authority over natural reason according to Baptist epistemological distinctives and congregational autonomy.

*** 1.2.2.20 Methodist/Wesleyan Response
Human knowledge participates in prevenient grace enabling rational-spiritual synthesis, requiring holistic approach transcending pure rationalism through personal holiness and social engagement according to Wesleyan epistemology.

*** 1.2.2.21 Eastern Orthodox Response
Human knowledge transcends rational limitations through theosis and divine energies, requiring spiritual transformation and patristic wisdom according to Orthodox epistemological understanding of mystical transcendence.

*** 1.2.2.22 Autocephalous Orthodox Response
Human knowledge maintains Orthodox theological integrity through autocephalous governance, expressing cultural epistemological distinctiveness while preserving essential theological principles according to canonical tradition.

*** 1.2.2.23 Orthodox Theological Schools Response
Human knowledge requires neo-patristic synthesis integrating patristic wisdom with contemporary scholarship, maintaining Orthodox epistemological integrity while engaging modern limitations according to academic methodology.

*** 1.2.2.24 Orthodox Monastic Response
Human knowledge transcends rational limitations through hesychast prayer and ascetical discipline, requiring spiritual transformation and contemplative experience according to athonite monastic wisdom.

*** 1.2.2.25 Orthodox Diaspora Response
Human knowledge maintains Orthodox spiritual understanding within multicultural contexts, adapting epistemological expression while preserving essential theological limitations according to diaspora experience.

*** 1.2.2.26 Coptic Orthodox Response
Human knowledge centers on Incarnation according to Cyrilline christology, requiring understanding of epistemological limits through divine-human unity according to Coptic theological tradition.

*** 1.2.2.27 Ethiopian Orthodox Response
Human knowledge flows through Tewahedo christology and Ethiopian covenant, integrating biblical and cultural epistemological understanding according to Ethiopian Orthodox synthesis.

*** 1.2.2.28 Eritrean Orthodox Response
Human knowledge manifests through Tewahedo faith and cultural independence, maintaining Orthodox epistemological understanding within Eritrean context.

*** 1.2.2.29 Syriac Orthodox Response
Human knowledge operates through divine-human unity according to West Syriac heritage, maintaining Jacobite epistemological understanding according to ancient tradition.

*** 1.2.2.30 Armenian Orthodox Response
Human knowledge flows through Armenian Apostolic tradition and cultural preservation, maintaining distinctive epistemological understanding through historical experience.

*** 1.2.2.31 Hasidic Response
Human knowledge contains divine sparks requiring mystical liberation, with rational limitations transcended through contemplative practice serving cosmic repair according to Hasidic epistemology.

*** 1.2.2.32 Lithuanian Orthodox Response
